WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.752
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.630 --> 00:00:07.800
SPEAKER: It's an
honor to be here.

00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:12.260
I wanted to begin by saying that
I've been interested in Cuba

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:14.510
for a long time.

00:00:14.510 --> 00:00:19.160
We have an employee named
Brett Perlmutter, who's here,

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:22.010
who's really one of the
heroes of the company, who,

00:00:22.010 --> 00:00:26.990
working with a team, has figured
out how we engage in Cuba.

00:00:26.990 --> 00:00:29.510
And Google's position
is that we want

00:00:29.510 --> 00:00:33.050
Cuba to be as successful
and connected as possible,

00:00:33.050 --> 00:00:35.840
and we've done our part.

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:42.170
And I went to Cuba 2 and
1/2 years ago, and then more

00:00:42.170 --> 00:00:44.900
recently, in December, so my
second visit, during which time

00:00:44.900 --> 00:00:47.270
I met with
[INAUDIBLE] Leal who's

00:00:47.270 --> 00:00:50.007
the historian of the country.

00:00:50.007 --> 00:00:52.340
And I thought it would be
interesting to talk about Cuba

00:00:52.340 --> 00:00:54.800
here with people
who are interested,

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:59.510
but also to honor your service
and commitment to your country.

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:07.390
So your background-- probably be
the most significant historian

00:01:07.390 --> 00:01:10.880
in the country,
officially has the title

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:14.050
of the historian of Havana.

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:16.370
But if you've been
to Havana, you

00:01:16.370 --> 00:01:20.830
know that it is the cultural
center of the country.

00:01:20.830 --> 00:01:28.670
And I thought we should start
by asking you about Jose Marti

00:01:28.670 --> 00:01:32.330
and why he's so important and
why you're here in New York.

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:39.480
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:01:49.750 --> 00:01:51.250
INTERPRETER: Well,
first of all, I'd

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:53.767
like to thank you all
for welcoming here,

00:01:53.767 --> 00:01:56.350
specifically to the headquarters
here in New York City, which,

00:01:56.350 --> 00:02:00.120
by the way, is absolutely
beautiful and inspiring.

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:02.380
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:17.170
INTERPRETER: I'm actually
in New York on, if you will,

00:02:17.170 --> 00:02:21.160
what is a romantic
visit of sorts.

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:22.720
20 years ago, I
came to New York,

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:25.120
and I found myself
in Central Park.

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:28.030
And I found a beautiful
sculpture of Jose Marti.

00:02:28.030 --> 00:02:30.210
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:02:51.730 --> 00:02:53.920
INTERPRETER: It was actually
put together or created

00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:57.370
by an artist, an American
artist, who was a bit avant

00:02:57.370 --> 00:03:00.190
garde in her creation,
because of the fact

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:02.320
that no other
sculpture of its type

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:06.940
had ever been seen of a poet,
historian, or statesman,

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:08.850
and it drew my attention.

00:03:08.850 --> 00:03:11.600
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:03:23.057 --> 00:03:24.890
INTERPRETER: Huntington,
who was the author,

00:03:24.890 --> 00:03:28.050
studied the Italian
school of culture,

00:03:28.050 --> 00:03:33.700
and she was able to take
the idea or personality

00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:36.640
behind Marti and really
hone in on his personality

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:37.800
to create this work of art.

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:39.523
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:03:49.546 --> 00:03:51.670
INTERPRETER: And, of course,
the type of technology

00:03:51.670 --> 00:03:53.740
that she used in
creating this went

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:55.720
against every kind
of school of thought

00:03:55.720 --> 00:03:59.790
at that time in the
creation of this monument.

00:03:59.790 --> 00:04:01.630
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:04:43.151 --> 00:04:44.650
INTERPRETER: And,
of course, an idea

00:04:44.650 --> 00:04:46.180
came to mind at
that time, which was

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:50.110
to create a work of art that was
similar to the same sculpture

00:04:50.110 --> 00:04:52.240
that I had seen in Central Park.

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:53.650
This was an idea
that, of course,

00:04:53.650 --> 00:04:55.810
took two decades in the making.

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:57.430
And at the moment,
I'm actually very

00:04:57.430 --> 00:05:01.180
close to coming to
fruition with that idea.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:04.060
And, of course, the idea
of creating a copy of this

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:07.810
is also to create the same
type of sensitivity and genius

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:13.600
that this artist used in
honing in on the life of Marti

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:15.620
here in New York
City, who actually--

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:19.420
he lived 15 years here
in New York, more time

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:20.770
here than he did in Cuba.

00:05:20.770 --> 00:05:23.620
And he experimented
with culture and all

00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:27.080
of the American
know-how at that time.

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:28.720
So, of course,
now at this point,

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:30.850
I'm trying to see
what I can do to bring

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:34.150
that same type of appeal that
is found in this work of art

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:40.310
to the city of Havana that
saw Marti be born in Cuba.

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:42.530
SPEAKER: It's interesting
that in Cuba, there

00:05:42.530 --> 00:05:47.360
are no statues of Fidel Castro.

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:50.570
And yet there is
a great reverence

00:05:50.570 --> 00:05:55.310
for both Fidel and Jose Marti.

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:59.720
Why is it that there are
no effigies of Fidel,

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:03.350
but you're very
focused on Marti?

00:06:03.350 --> 00:06:06.020
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:06:56.120 --> 00:06:58.370
INTERPRETER: He was
completely against any sort

00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:01.190
of cult of personality,
anything that

00:07:01.190 --> 00:07:05.540
involved creating monuments
or statues or plazas

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:07.580
or institutions.

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:12.410
And he was completely
in tune with the idea

00:07:12.410 --> 00:07:15.620
that Marti tried to leave
for the world, which

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:18.030
was to create a better world.

00:07:18.030 --> 00:07:21.290
He then himself knew that
Marti believed in this,

00:07:21.290 --> 00:07:22.670
and it was emblematic.

00:07:22.670 --> 00:07:26.570
You would probably say that my
words are a bit contradictory

00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:31.730
in what Fidel wanted, but in
essence, his passion will also

00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:33.530
be part of this statue.

00:07:33.530 --> 00:07:35.510
And it's also the
America that Marti

00:07:35.510 --> 00:07:37.470
wanted to create, our America.

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:42.550
SPEAKER: So Google has
also helped with Marti

00:07:42.550 --> 00:07:46.780
by building a virtual
reality demonstration

00:07:46.780 --> 00:07:52.290
that we have showed off
for using our VR goggles.

00:07:52.290 --> 00:07:56.850
And so I'd like to
understand a little bit more

00:07:56.850 --> 00:08:02.370
about the history of Havana
and its preservation.

00:08:02.370 --> 00:08:05.370
You were heavily
involved in making

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:08.520
Havana become a
UNESCO World site

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:12.300
and preventing its development.

00:08:12.300 --> 00:08:14.550
Was that your idea?

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:17.250
Was that Fidel's idea?

00:08:17.250 --> 00:08:19.880
How did it really work?

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:59.882
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:08:59.882 --> 00:09:01.340
INTERPRETER: First
of all, I'd like

00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:04.960
to thank Google for the
creation of the goggles,

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:10.250
where children are able to sort
of witness the history that's

00:09:10.250 --> 00:09:12.830
been played out in Havana
for a very long time.

00:09:12.830 --> 00:09:15.390
It's almost as if their feet
have been held to the fire,

00:09:15.390 --> 00:09:17.764
so to speak, so that they can
actually witness everything

00:09:17.764 --> 00:09:19.100
that's happening in real time.

00:09:19.100 --> 00:09:24.440
And secondly, the restoration
of the Cuban Civic Center

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:29.180
for History, which has now
seen a Renaissance in what

00:09:29.180 --> 00:09:32.880
is the new history that
will be created in Cuba.

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:34.790
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:09:51.980 --> 00:09:53.960
INTERPRETER: Of
course, in keeping

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:56.930
with the tradition of
Spanish literature,

00:09:56.930 --> 00:09:59.690
which is always to look back
into the past and sort of look

00:09:59.690 --> 00:10:02.630
at everything romantically and
think that the past is always

00:10:02.630 --> 00:10:04.670
better than the present
or even the future,

00:10:04.670 --> 00:10:08.180
this sort of seems to
be the proper setting

00:10:08.180 --> 00:10:10.790
for the narration of this film.

00:10:10.790 --> 00:10:14.180
And of course, this
would be the best link

00:10:14.180 --> 00:10:16.072
for the past to the future.

00:10:16.072 --> 00:10:17.780
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:37.100
INTERPRETER: Of
course, this idea

00:10:37.100 --> 00:10:39.710
was never really
understood, and I'd

00:10:39.710 --> 00:10:43.400
like to hearken back to what I'd
like to call heroic times about

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:46.310
four decades ago, where I was
walking through the streets

00:10:46.310 --> 00:10:48.980
and collecting all
sorts of information

00:10:48.980 --> 00:10:51.080
to then be able to
recount all of this

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:52.610
and use this as a
point of departure

00:10:52.610 --> 00:10:54.332
for this kind of
[INAUDIBLE] project.

00:10:54.332 --> 00:10:56.040
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:10:59.231 --> 00:11:00.730
INTERPRETER: Of
course, I then found

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:03.350
faithful workers, who
accompanied me on this task,

00:11:03.350 --> 00:11:05.010
or adventure, if you will.

00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:06.910
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:09.470
INTERPRETER: My car
only had two wheels.

00:11:09.470 --> 00:11:11.260
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:11:44.117 --> 00:11:45.825
INTERPRETER: And of
course, at that time,

00:11:45.825 --> 00:11:48.610
Alejo Carpentier, one
of the contributors

00:11:48.610 --> 00:11:52.900
to the American letters, saw
this very thin, frail, young

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:55.540
boy walking down the streets
with a load of rocks.

00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:58.180
And he asked, who is this boy?

00:11:58.180 --> 00:12:00.760
And someone said,
someone who's actually

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:02.690
chasing an impossible dream.

00:12:02.690 --> 00:12:04.450
And he said, he will
probably make it.

00:12:04.450 --> 00:12:08.140
He will probably get very far
with that two-wheeled cart.

00:12:08.140 --> 00:12:09.820
And it's actually
prophetic on his part

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:11.160
that he actually said that.

00:12:11.160 --> 00:12:12.910
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:12:15.022 --> 00:12:16.480
INTERPRETER: At
that point, my work

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:20.180
actually became a sort of
Greek republic, if you will.

00:12:20.180 --> 00:12:22.080
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:12:26.485 --> 00:12:28.360
INTERPRETER: Since I
had to create everything

00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:29.860
from its inception,
it's as though I

00:12:29.860 --> 00:12:34.470
had to create both the bow
and arrow at that point.

00:12:34.470 --> 00:12:37.195
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:12:44.447 --> 00:12:46.030
INTERPRETER: Of
course, at that point,

00:12:46.030 --> 00:12:48.490
Fidel came to me with a
delegation from Chile.

00:12:48.490 --> 00:12:51.220
He came to old Havana,
and apparently, someone

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:53.570
had mentioned what
I was trying to do.

00:12:53.570 --> 00:12:56.490
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:13:04.002 --> 00:13:05.460
INTERPRETER: And
of course, he then

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:06.760
asked me, what is
it that you need?

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:08.426
This was after he had
finished his tour.

00:13:08.426 --> 00:13:09.760
And I said, absolutely nothing.

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:13.260
And he said, if I asked you for
something, you won't come back.

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:15.132
He laughed, and he
laughed a lot, actually.

00:13:15.132 --> 00:13:15.840
And then he left.

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:17.548
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:13:25.722 --> 00:13:27.180
INTERPRETER: And
of course, instead

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:28.920
of being a subordinate
of his or someone

00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:32.190
that was in need of something,
he actually became a benefactor

00:13:32.190 --> 00:13:33.580
to this grand opus.

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:36.612
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:13:36.612 --> 00:13:38.820
INTERPRETER: And that's how
the project actually came

00:13:38.820 --> 00:13:40.650
to its inception as it is now.

00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:42.710
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:14:03.246 --> 00:14:06.810
INTERPRETER: At that point,
many fortresses in the island,

00:14:06.810 --> 00:14:10.140
on the island-- over
50 palaces, churches,

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:12.850
and all sorts of
plazas and arches--

00:14:12.850 --> 00:14:15.030
began to be refurbished.

00:14:15.030 --> 00:14:19.087
Radio and TV also lent
their help to this,

00:14:19.087 --> 00:14:21.420
and it was all to sort of
create the infrastructure that

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:25.020
was necessary so that then
the information could also

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:26.852
be published.

00:14:26.852 --> 00:14:28.560
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:34.050
INTERPRETER: I gave up on using
my cell phone about a year ago.

00:14:34.050 --> 00:14:35.759
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:14:35.759 --> 00:14:37.716
INTERPRETER: That means
if you need to find me,

00:14:37.716 --> 00:14:38.560
you will find me.

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:40.460
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:41.450
INTERPRETER: Whoever
needs to seek me

00:14:41.450 --> 00:14:42.740
out will definitely find me.

00:14:42.740 --> 00:14:44.060
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:14:44.060 --> 00:14:45.525
INTERPRETER: I'm
actually free now.

00:14:45.525 --> 00:14:47.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:48.925 --> 00:14:50.300
SPEAKER: One of
the things that I

00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:57.800
learned from you is that the
Spanish Cuban American history

00:14:57.800 --> 00:15:01.440
was more complicated
than I thought.

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:05.990
And I learned from you
that the Cubans fought

00:15:05.990 --> 00:15:11.210
with the Americans
against the British

00:15:11.210 --> 00:15:14.930
and that Cuba was a
very important part

00:15:14.930 --> 00:15:19.700
of the Spanish empire, and
much of their Caribbean work

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:21.890
was done from
Havana, which is why

00:15:21.890 --> 00:15:25.500
Havana is such a rich place.

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:29.410
Tell us a little bit about all
of that part of the history.

00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:31.670
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:46.140
INTERPRETER: When the very first
lamp was filled with whale oil

00:15:46.140 --> 00:15:47.880
on the streets of
Havana, the Puritans

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:51.060
hadn't actually reached the
United States yet, or America,

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:51.950
for that matter.

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:54.564
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:15:54.564 --> 00:15:56.730
INTERPRETER: Only Spain
surrounded us at that point.

00:15:56.730 --> 00:15:58.438
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:15:58.438 --> 00:16:00.070
INTERPRETER: Even
so, even Florida was.

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:01.920
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:03.470
INTERPRETER: And, of course,
the North was unexplored.

00:16:03.470 --> 00:16:05.590
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:06.417 --> 00:16:08.250
INTERPRETER: Some
expeditionists had already

00:16:08.250 --> 00:16:09.330
been to those areas.

00:16:09.330 --> 00:16:11.990
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:14.100 --> 00:16:16.350
INTERPRETER: The
Mississippi River

00:16:16.350 --> 00:16:20.230
was as legendary as was the
Amazon or the Magdalena River.

00:16:20.230 --> 00:16:22.570
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:29.460
INTERPRETER: When Havana was
taken by the British in 1762--

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:31.620
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:31.620 --> 00:16:34.200
INTERPRETER: --after a siege
that took about two months--

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:36.410
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:40.959 --> 00:16:42.750
INTERPRETER: --they
arrived at the capital,

00:16:42.750 --> 00:16:46.620
and they set up what
was the British control

00:16:46.620 --> 00:16:48.120
of the western
part of the island.

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:50.280
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:57.057 --> 00:16:59.640
INTERPRETER: Among those young
officials that arrived in Cuba,

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:02.340
there was a young man,
a very tall young man

00:17:02.340 --> 00:17:03.540
named George Washington.

00:17:03.540 --> 00:17:05.470
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:06.585 --> 00:17:08.460
INTERPRETER: Perhaps no
one knew at that time

00:17:08.460 --> 00:17:10.709
that he would eventually
become the liberator-- excuse

00:17:10.709 --> 00:17:12.569
me-- the founder of
the United States.

00:17:12.569 --> 00:17:15.280
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:16.307 --> 00:17:18.890
INTERPRETER: That's where this
relationship actually was born.

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:20.598
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:20.598 --> 00:17:23.060
INTERPRETER: A very strong
economic relationship.

00:17:23.060 --> 00:17:23.490
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:23.490 --> 00:17:25.281
INTERPRETER: Between
Cuba and the colonies.

00:17:25.281 --> 00:17:27.890
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:29.094 --> 00:17:30.510
INTERPRETER: And,
of course, Spain

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:33.090
wanted to avenge this hostility
that it had towards Britain.

00:17:33.090 --> 00:17:36.030
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:37.176 --> 00:17:39.300
INTERPRETER: And when the
first cry of independence

00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:41.630
took place in America,
Spain heard it.

00:17:41.630 --> 00:17:43.350
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:45.734 --> 00:17:47.400
INTERPRETER: And the
very first platform

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:51.170
of help for that event to take
place was the port of Havana.

00:17:51.170 --> 00:17:53.100
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:54.764 --> 00:17:56.430
INTERPRETER: There
is still a stone that

00:17:56.430 --> 00:17:58.430
reads, "The port of liberty."

00:17:58.430 --> 00:18:00.370
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:18:05.219 --> 00:18:07.260
INTERPRETER: And, of
course, emissaries from Cuba

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:11.890
arrived at George Washington's
camp in Georgetown.

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:13.650
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:18.450
INTERPRETER: He was
able to identify them,

00:18:18.450 --> 00:18:19.991
because, of course,
they all belonged

00:18:19.991 --> 00:18:21.320
to the same Masonic society.

00:18:21.320 --> 00:18:23.475
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:18:31.002 --> 00:18:32.460
INTERPRETER: Who
obviously believed

00:18:32.460 --> 00:18:37.680
in the future, that believed in
the brotherhood or camaraderie

00:18:37.680 --> 00:18:40.560
among human beings, that
believed in progress,

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:42.792
and believed in the
betterment of society.

00:18:42.792 --> 00:18:44.500
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:18:57.662 --> 00:18:59.370
INTERPRETER: So, of
course, now that I've

00:18:59.370 --> 00:19:01.650
had a chance to get this
out to the United States,

00:19:01.650 --> 00:19:05.970
I've been in St. Augustine, I've
been in Pensacola, and Mobile.

00:19:05.970 --> 00:19:10.950
I've seen some of the
cemeteries, and some of them

00:19:10.950 --> 00:19:13.320
remind me of those
luminaries from Cuba.

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:15.660
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:17.315 --> 00:19:18.690
INTERPRETER: And,
of course, when

00:19:18.690 --> 00:19:22.220
Cuba began to fight for its
own independence in 1868--

00:19:22.220 --> 00:19:24.734
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:24.734 --> 00:19:26.400
INTERPRETER: --many
Americans, actually,

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:29.655
supported and sympathized
the Cuban struggle.

00:19:29.655 --> 00:19:31.470
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:31.470 --> 00:19:33.930
INTERPRETER: And many of them
also went to fight for Cuba.

00:19:33.930 --> 00:19:36.140
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:36.690 --> 00:19:39.545
INTERPRETER: And they, too,
are part of our history.

00:19:39.545 --> 00:19:42.300
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:44.600
INTERPRETER: Those are the
most interpretive keys or--

00:19:44.600 --> 00:19:46.524
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:46.524 --> 00:19:47.940
INTERPRETER: So,
of course, we are

00:19:47.940 --> 00:19:49.590
tied because of these things.

00:19:49.590 --> 00:19:52.810
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:53.310 --> 00:19:54.750
INTERPRETER: And
of course, Marti

00:19:54.750 --> 00:19:56.890
was the supreme symbol
of those ideals.

00:19:56.890 --> 00:19:58.850
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:04.936 --> 00:20:06.810
INTERPRETER: And of
course, his last birthday

00:20:06.810 --> 00:20:10.080
was the 28th of January,
1895, in the Delmonico

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:11.970
Cafe in New York.

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:13.940
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:13.940 --> 00:20:16.712
INTERPRETER: And then after
that, he went back to Cuba.

00:20:16.712 --> 00:20:18.420
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:18.420 --> 00:20:20.380
INTERPRETER: He was
only 42 years of age.

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:23.210
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:25.011 --> 00:20:26.760
INTERPRETER: And as I
mentioned yesterday,

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:31.450
his life was as ephemeral
as that of a butterfly's.

00:20:31.450 --> 00:20:33.050
SPEAKER: I have
one more question,

00:20:33.050 --> 00:20:35.017
and then we'll go to
the audience questions.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:44.920
Today, the links between Cuba
and America are being restored.

00:20:44.920 --> 00:20:47.440
What is your hope
for the relations

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:49.836
between Cuba and Americans?

00:20:49.836 --> 00:20:50.960
What would you like to see?

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:55.840
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:59.242 --> 00:21:00.950
INTERPRETER: I'd like
to repeat something

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:02.120
that I mentioned before.

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:04.430
Cuba has always had,
has, and will always

00:21:04.430 --> 00:21:06.140
have friends in
the United States.

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:09.060
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:14.194 --> 00:21:16.610
INTERPRETER: Political battles
should never become vulgar.

00:21:16.610 --> 00:21:18.645
They should only be
a battle of ideas.

00:21:18.645 --> 00:21:21.230
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:22.377 --> 00:21:24.710
INTERPRETER: I cannot believe,
nor do I want to believe,

00:21:24.710 --> 00:21:27.525
that we are doomed to have
this enmity among us forever.

00:21:27.525 --> 00:21:29.440
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:32.397 --> 00:21:34.730
INTERPRETER: And the most
flagrant manifestation of that

00:21:34.730 --> 00:21:37.510
is the constant
blockade of Cuba.

00:21:37.510 --> 00:21:39.410
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:42.110
INTERPRETER: Now that invisible
wall is finally crumbling.

00:21:42.110 --> 00:21:43.880
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:46.707 --> 00:21:49.040
INTERPRETER: What we cannot
allow to see happen again is

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:52.380
that those gaps, again, are
filled with chains that we can

00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:53.010
no longer open.

00:21:53.010 --> 00:21:54.781
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:55.176 --> 00:21:57.550
INTERPRETER: We do not burn
North American flags in Cuba.

00:21:57.550 --> 00:21:59.258
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:59.258 --> 00:22:01.250
INTERPRETER: And
Americans are not stones.

00:22:01.250 --> 00:22:03.020
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:22:04.097 --> 00:22:05.930
INTERPRETER: Our
emigration from the country

00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:07.410
has always been towards
the United States.

00:22:07.410 --> 00:22:09.190
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:22:12.510 --> 00:22:14.510
INTERPRETER: I remember
there was a senator that

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:16.301
visited me several
years ago, actually, one

00:22:16.301 --> 00:22:17.720
of the most important senators.

00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:19.630
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:22:20.497 --> 00:22:22.580
INTERPRETER: And of course,
after the conversation

00:22:22.580 --> 00:22:24.732
was over, the blockade
was total at that point.

00:22:24.732 --> 00:22:26.440
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:22:26.780 --> 00:22:28.280
INTERPRETER: And
he said to me, what

00:22:28.280 --> 00:22:30.821
is it that you would like for
me to bring you from the United

00:22:30.821 --> 00:22:32.010
States on my next visit?

00:22:32.010 --> 00:22:34.290
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:22:34.372 --> 00:22:36.080
INTERPRETER: And I
said to him, would you

00:22:36.080 --> 00:22:38.692
be so generous as to be
able to accomplish that?

00:22:38.692 --> 00:22:40.400
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:22:41.964 --> 00:22:43.380
INTERPRETER: And
I said, would you

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:45.680
please be able to bring me
an Oil Spice shaving cream?

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:47.530
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:22:47.530 --> 00:22:48.290
INTERPRETER: The most
interesting thing

00:22:48.290 --> 00:22:50.270
is that he actually made
[INAUDIBLE] to his promise.

00:22:50.270 --> 00:22:51.227
He brought it for me.

00:22:51.227 --> 00:22:52.560
He came back, and he brought it.

00:22:52.560 --> 00:22:56.140
SPEAKER: I'm sure we can buy
it around the corner here.

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:58.550
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:23:00.842 --> 00:23:02.300
INTERPRETER: I
really do appreciate

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:04.290
the senator's noble gesture.

00:23:04.290 --> 00:23:06.050
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:23:06.050 --> 00:23:06.950
INTERPRETER: And I
believe that that

00:23:06.950 --> 00:23:08.290
is what we need to aspire to.

00:23:08.290 --> 00:23:11.040
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:13.165
INTERPRETER: Now that
the world is just

00:23:13.165 --> 00:23:15.260
such a difficult place,
a complicated place.

00:23:15.260 --> 00:23:18.230
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:23:18.230 --> 00:23:20.900
INTERPRETER: I think we
need to look for and strive

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:24.010
for that harmonious
connection between people.

00:23:24.010 --> 00:23:26.120
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:23:29.435 --> 00:23:31.310
INTERPRETER: Where faith
and social doctrines

00:23:31.310 --> 00:23:33.382
do not separate us
from each other.

00:23:33.382 --> 00:23:35.090
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:23:35.090 --> 00:23:36.950
INTERPRETER: At least
that's my vision.

00:23:36.950 --> 00:23:39.050
SPEAKER: So with that,
do we have some questions

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:40.102
from the audience?

00:23:40.102 --> 00:23:42.560
And please ask them in Spanish
if you're a Spanish speaker,

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:45.600
and we'll have our
translator translate.

00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:47.040
Who'd like to start?

00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:54.192
Yes?

00:23:54.192 --> 00:23:55.900
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:23:55.900 --> 00:23:57.070
SPEAKER: Sir, go ahead.

00:23:57.070 --> 00:23:59.097
Please, please take
advantage of the situation

00:23:59.097 --> 00:23:59.930
to ask any question.

00:24:03.850 --> 00:24:07.030
AUDIENCE: [SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:24:28.860 --> 00:24:31.370
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:24:31.370 --> 00:24:33.770
INTERPRETER: I was recently
in Cuba a few weeks ago,

00:24:33.770 --> 00:24:35.644
and I'd like to ask you
a question concerning

00:24:35.644 --> 00:24:37.310
the restoration of
the infrastructure,

00:24:37.310 --> 00:24:39.710
specifically the buildings.

00:24:39.710 --> 00:24:42.320
Do you think that
that is in the works?

00:24:42.320 --> 00:24:44.030
Is the work being sped up?

00:24:44.030 --> 00:24:48.662
How long do you foresee that
happening in the near future?

00:24:48.662 --> 00:24:50.370
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:26:21.270 --> 00:26:23.690
INTERPRETER: And since you
say that, I believe so.

00:26:23.690 --> 00:26:26.260
I believe so that we
will be able to do that.

00:26:26.260 --> 00:26:31.090
I've recently been studying a
lot of the monuments in Cuba,

00:26:31.090 --> 00:26:35.080
and I've been working with
architects and archaeologists.

00:26:35.080 --> 00:26:40.120
Recently, we've tried to locate
the remains of the old city

00:26:40.120 --> 00:26:40.870
walls.

00:26:40.870 --> 00:26:42.670
Unfortunately, those
remains are now

00:26:42.670 --> 00:26:44.740
covered by parking
lots for buses

00:26:44.740 --> 00:26:46.900
of all types, tourist buses.

00:26:46.900 --> 00:26:50.890
And you know, at that
point, I said, break it all.

00:26:50.890 --> 00:26:52.740
If you need to open
the streets, do so.

00:26:52.740 --> 00:26:54.490
And I'm the kind of
person that's actually

00:26:54.490 --> 00:26:57.760
been very lucky and fortunate,
because every time I crack open

00:26:57.760 --> 00:27:00.040
the street, I find
something below.

00:27:00.040 --> 00:27:02.650
We did find the remains
of the city wall,

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:06.640
and we're very happy
about that at this moment.

00:27:06.640 --> 00:27:11.080
And with that same spirit, we
hope to pursue other projects.

00:27:11.080 --> 00:27:13.570
You know, it's
very easy to build,

00:27:13.570 --> 00:27:15.640
but it's very
difficult to restore.

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:19.180
And unfortunately, we haven't
been very lucky in the area,

00:27:19.180 --> 00:27:20.890
in the economic arena.

00:27:20.890 --> 00:27:23.890
You know, it's funny something
like UNESCO will grant me

00:27:23.890 --> 00:27:26.200
a title of a count,
but they won't

00:27:26.200 --> 00:27:28.180
allow us to receive
the money that we

00:27:28.180 --> 00:27:31.090
need to do this to
make sure that we

00:27:31.090 --> 00:27:37.090
can improve upon our national
heritage, which is our city.

00:27:37.090 --> 00:27:41.725
It's easier to get blood than it
is to get money in some cases.

00:27:41.725 --> 00:27:43.620
SPEAKER: Do we have
a question here?

00:27:43.620 --> 00:27:44.270
Yes, sir.

00:27:44.270 --> 00:27:46.980
AUDIENCE: [SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:28:14.474 --> 00:28:16.390
INTERPRETER: Thank you
so much for being here.

00:28:16.390 --> 00:28:18.348
Thank you so very much
for your wisdom as well.

00:28:18.348 --> 00:28:22.500
I'd like to put a rather
uncomfortable question to you,

00:28:22.500 --> 00:28:23.560
if you will.

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:26.280
But there is a long history
of American companies

00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:28.320
that have gone to
Cuba specifically

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:31.800
to exploit its riches.

00:28:31.800 --> 00:28:35.710
What can you say at the
moment about the situation?

00:28:35.710 --> 00:28:38.760
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:29:44.620 --> 00:29:47.560
INTERPRETER: Again, if you
ask me this question now,

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:50.440
and if I am put to the
alternative knowing

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:52.215
full well what's
being offered to us,

00:29:52.215 --> 00:29:54.340
I think the most important
thing now is that now we

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:56.900
are stewards of our own future.

00:29:56.900 --> 00:30:02.130
We are stewards of our own
sky and our own land in Cuba.

00:30:02.130 --> 00:30:03.940
And it is up to
us now to decide.

00:30:03.940 --> 00:30:05.380
Perhaps in the
past, it would have

00:30:05.380 --> 00:30:08.901
been more difficult
to decide what to do,

00:30:08.901 --> 00:30:09.900
what to do in this case.

00:30:09.900 --> 00:30:12.010
What are our choices?

00:30:12.010 --> 00:30:16.210
The alternative that is before
us now is an interesting one,

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:19.630
and again, I will say
this for a second time.

00:30:19.630 --> 00:30:24.550
The word, romantic--
revolutions are not romantic.

00:30:24.550 --> 00:30:27.550
But I would be hard
pressed to believe

00:30:27.550 --> 00:30:31.000
that if I saw a revolution
that wasn't romantic,

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.874
I would probably be
very doubtful of it.

00:30:34.874 --> 00:30:36.740
SPEAKER: Yes, sir.

00:30:36.740 --> 00:30:38.690
AUDIENCE: [SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:30:47.492 --> 00:30:48.950
INTERPRETER: What
do you believe is

00:30:48.950 --> 00:30:51.450
one of the most important things
that Americans need to know

00:30:51.450 --> 00:30:53.730
to change their view on Cuba?

00:30:53.730 --> 00:30:56.220
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:32:06.112 --> 00:32:08.320
INTERPRETER: The first thing
I'd like for you to know

00:32:08.320 --> 00:32:10.510
is that Cuba is a friendly
and hospitable country.

00:32:10.510 --> 00:32:14.530
We welcome any and
all to our country.

00:32:14.530 --> 00:32:16.720
If there are athletes
present, and, of course,

00:32:16.720 --> 00:32:18.303
their national anthem
is being played,

00:32:18.303 --> 00:32:19.562
everyone stands in respect.

00:32:19.562 --> 00:32:21.520
If you're walking down
the street as a tourist,

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:22.570
people greet you.

00:32:22.570 --> 00:32:25.780
The most important thing is
that we have different views

00:32:25.780 --> 00:32:27.365
and different ways of thinking.

00:32:27.365 --> 00:32:28.990
And of course, there
are certain dogmas

00:32:28.990 --> 00:32:31.450
that have been
imposed, particularly

00:32:31.450 --> 00:32:34.660
in the realm of economics.

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:37.390
The United States is one of
the only countries in the world

00:32:37.390 --> 00:32:39.250
that cannot visit Cuba openly.

00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:41.200
Its citizens cannot
visit Cuba openly.

00:32:41.200 --> 00:32:47.860
It is easier for you to visit
the democratic country of North

00:32:47.860 --> 00:32:50.470
Korea than it is to visit Cuba.

00:32:50.470 --> 00:32:54.670
We are tied by historical,
poetic, and artistic ties,

00:32:54.670 --> 00:32:56.830
and that is what we
need to focus on.

00:32:56.830 --> 00:33:01.300
And we need to make sure that we
vanquish any sort of separatism

00:33:01.300 --> 00:33:02.140
on our part.

00:33:02.140 --> 00:33:05.010
It is time to destroy
any kind of wall

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:06.790
that we may have
built in the past.

00:33:06.790 --> 00:33:09.100
It is time to unite,
and it is time

00:33:09.100 --> 00:33:14.290
to remember that we are
more together than we think.

00:33:14.290 --> 00:33:17.590
SPEAKER: As a person who's been
to North Korea and to Cuba,

00:33:17.590 --> 00:33:21.280
I can tell you it's easier
to get to North Korea.

00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:24.640
So Professor is correct.

00:33:24.640 --> 00:33:29.680
The good news is if you've
not been to Cuba before, it's

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:34.210
relatively easy to go under
one of 12 categories now,

00:33:34.210 --> 00:33:37.770
and I would strongly
recommend that you visit.

00:33:37.770 --> 00:33:40.750
Strong, strong recommendation
that you visit.

00:33:40.750 --> 00:33:43.070
Yes, ma'am.

00:33:43.070 --> 00:33:44.620
AUDIENCE: [SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:34:16.915 --> 00:34:19.040
INTERPRETER: Thank you so
very much for being here.

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:23.389
I'm so happy about this new era
which is being born in Cuba.

00:34:23.389 --> 00:34:26.420
I'd like to know
what you think is--

00:34:26.420 --> 00:34:29.040
what is your dream for
Cuba at the moment,

00:34:29.040 --> 00:34:31.210
particularly for the future?

00:34:31.210 --> 00:34:34.226
EUSEBIO LEAL SPENGLER:
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:35:52.349 --> 00:35:54.140
INTERPRETER: Every
single error, of course,

00:35:54.140 --> 00:35:56.390
poses its own challenges.

00:35:56.390 --> 00:36:00.020
And sometimes those challenges
are not prudent at the moment.

00:36:00.020 --> 00:36:02.780
And of course, with the opening
of the relations between Cuba

00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:05.240
and the United States,
there are many things that

00:36:05.240 --> 00:36:06.890
still need to be worked out.

00:36:06.890 --> 00:36:08.870
There are many
delicate issues that

00:36:08.870 --> 00:36:10.760
still need to be talked about.

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:14.980
But I believe that we are
definitely on the right path.

00:36:14.980 --> 00:36:18.110
My dream, my wish
for Cuba is that Cuba

00:36:18.110 --> 00:36:20.810
will become more participatory,
that its population will

00:36:20.810 --> 00:36:23.930
be more involved in its future,
that there will be more equity,

00:36:23.930 --> 00:36:25.700
and that there will
be more prosperity.

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:29.000
Of course, the Cuba of
yesteryear, the Cuba from two,

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.940
three years ago will no
longer be in existence,

00:36:31.940 --> 00:36:34.940
that people will be
able to have a life full

00:36:34.940 --> 00:36:39.770
of dignity, that, of course,
the difference, the anguishing

00:36:39.770 --> 00:36:43.410
difference that richness
versus poverty poses

00:36:43.410 --> 00:36:46.100
will also allow people
to live a better life,

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:49.340
and ultimately, that there
is more justice for everyone.

00:36:49.340 --> 00:36:51.470
That is the main goal,
and that is the thing

00:36:51.470 --> 00:36:55.260
that I am dreaming for in Cuba.

00:36:55.260 --> 00:36:56.370
SPEAKER: Yes, sir.

00:36:56.370 --> 00:36:58.420
And I think we
have one following,

00:36:58.420 --> 00:37:00.250
and these will be our
last two questions.

00:37:00.250 --> 00:37:01.886
So yes, sir.

